<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1300]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1060,1085]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Comments.</emphasis>
All samples of this species have been collected at only one site in Alstonville, 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15627" box="[1295,1357,1060,1084]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15627" name="Royal Botanic Gardens, National Herbarium of New South Wales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">NSW</collectionCode>
on an ornamental specimen of its native host. The pale colouration combined with number and location of glandular spines should clearly distinguish this species from any other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[979,1142,1132,1156]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Aleurocanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[979,1142,1132,1156]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Aleurocanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1182,1289,1132,1156]" name="Australia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Australia</collectingCountry>
. The species appears close to 
<taxonomicName box="[340,451,1168,1192]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Aleurocanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosa">
<emphasis box="[340,451,1168,1192]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. rugosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[508,639,1168,1192]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Aleurocanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sapindus">
<emphasis box="[508,639,1168,1192]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. sapindus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Distinctive characters they share include clear/pale colour with some mottling in the dorsum and a margin concentric row of numerous small setae (possibly glandular in nature) in the submargin. 
<taxonomicName box="[282,392,1240,1264]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Aleurocanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ashleyi">
<emphasis box="[282,392,1240,1264]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. ashleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from these by having more numerous glandular spines on the dorsum and a distinctive serrate margin.
</paragraph>
